It is easy to generate human-imperceptible perturbations that put prediction of a deep neural network (DNN) out. Such perturbed samples are called adversarial examples (
            , 
          ) and algorithms for generating adversarial examples are called adversarial attacks.
It is well known that adversarial attacks can greatly reduce the accuracy of DNNs, for example from about 96% accuracy on clean data to almost zero accuracy on adversarial examples (
            , 
          ). This vulnerability of DNNs can cause serious security problems when DNNs are applied to security critical applications (
            , 
          ) such as medicine (
            , 
          ) and autonomous driving (
            , 
          ).

